    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
                546 N. 5 St<lb/>
                Philadelphia Pa<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/> 
            <p>No.92 E 111St<lb/>
                N. Y. 1 Jany<lb/>&#47;85<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Mr. Morais&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have<lb/> just heard with real regret<lb/> that you do not intend to<lb/> attend the Ministers&#39; Conference<lb/> to be held here this month.<lb/></p>
            <p>Will you pardon my in&#45;<lb/>truding upon what is entirely<lb/> your affair&#63; I think it<lb/> is really a great mistake <del>to</del><lb/> hold aloof from such a meeting.<lb/> It seems to me that Con&#45;<lb/>servatism has been much to<lb/> blame for the errors that the<lb/> radicals have made in failing<lb/> to check those errors in their<lb/> incipiency. It may be that<lb/> heretofore opportunity has not<lb/> offered for such checks&#44; but<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>I believe that the spirit of<lb/> Conservatism has been such as<lb/> would not have availed itself<lb/> of any opportunity which might<lb/> have been at hand. If I<lb/> read aright the evident signs<lb/> of the times there is today a<lb/> <del>gradu&#91;&#63;&#93;</del> tendency to retrace some<lb/> of the radical steps. It appears<lb/> at least to be conceded that<lb/> change and innovation have gone<lb/> far enough and there seems<lb/> rather to be an effort to reju<lb/>venate old than to introduce<lb/> new customs. Now&#44; has Con&#45;<lb/>servatism nothing to aid in<lb/> this work&#63; It is no word of<lb/> flattery when I say that in&#45;<lb/>stinctively we turn to you<lb/> as our leader. I&#44; as an in&#45;<lb/>dividual Jew&#44; feel that I ought<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>to be represented in the Conference and that I<lb/> will not be represented in your absence.<lb/> No man like yourself stands in the Ameri&#45;<lb/>can Jewish Community for an intelligent<lb/> liberal and consistently progressive Conserva&#45;<lb/>tism. Unless I have much misunderstood<lb/> your teachings&#44; you do not believe that<lb/> any Minhag is of divine ordination and<lb/> therefore externally fixed&#8212;consequently a<lb/> fair and fine discussion &#40;and I think this<lb/> conference proposes only to discuss&#41; cannot<lb/> be <sic>vaneful</sic> and may be beneficent. But<lb/> there can be no good influence excited&#44;<lb/> either by you in your personality or as the<lb/> representative of those people for whom you<lb/> would speak &#44; if you will not confer with<lb/> the others. The Ministers&#39; Association in<lb/> Phil<hi rend="sup">a</hi> did good work there&#8212;why cannot<lb/> this larger scheme do equally well. I do<lb/> not know but I believe that an Eastern<lb/> College will be proposed at no distant day<lb/> Does not this require co&#45;operation&#63;<lb/></p>
            <p>I hope that you will reconsider and deter&#45;<lb/>mine to come. I know that you will appre&#45;<lb/>ciate the motives that prompt this letter and<lb/> will therefore not regard it as impertinent.<lb/></p>
            <p>Ever Faithfully Yours			Cyrus L. Sulzberger<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
